							Man's House Move Leaves Neighbors Cold
						</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td style="font-size: 11pt;"> 
							 
							<br>
							<br>
							10:59 PM EST January 28, 2003 
							<br>
							The Associated Press<br><br><br>ADA TOWNSHIP, Mich.<p class="nitfp">When power was shut down to move the home of a prominent family, hundreds of residents found themselves without heat or electricity - some for hours - on one of the coldest days of the year.</p>
<p class="nitfp">"I worry about the lady who lives down the street and is blind," said Lillie Jones, 89. "Why couldn't they just do it in the summer?"</p>
<p class="nitfp">Utility crews temporarily shut off power and removed some overhead lines to move the sprawling home of Alticor Inc. Chairman Steve Van Andel six miles on Monday - when the high temperature was only 15 degrees.</p>
<p class="nitfp">Jones said she spent Monday evening resetting clocks and waiting for her own home to warm up after her power was off for five hours during the move, which started shortly after 10 a.m. and ended about 6 p.m.</p>
<p class="nitfp">"I've been freezing," she said.</p>
<p class="nitfp">The power company sent notices to news organizations and a contractor who moved the home said he personally contacted homeowners about the planned outage. But Jones and some other residents said they were unaware of the outage until it happened.</p>
<p class="nitfp">Van Andel apologized to neighbors Tuesday in a two-sentence statement issued by Alticor, the parent company of Amway.</p>
<p class="nitfp">"When we made plans to move our home, we tried to minimize any disruption to our neighbors," the statement said. "My wife and I are truly sorry for any inconvenience we may have caused."</p>
<p class="nitfp">Consumers Energy spokesman Kevin Keane said he believed the total number of customers who lost power was less than 1,000 - about 300 at a time as the move progressed.</p>
<p class="nitfp">The nearly 6,000-square-foot house is valued at $632,000. Van Andel plans to build a new house on the old 10-acre lot.</p>

